how long will it take? scaling

qualitative analysis: scaling of run time/memory requirements with

  • dimension
  • number of observations
  • number of groups (for multilevel models)
  • number of parameters
  • etc.

Use small runs (large enough for stability, e.g.>1 min) to estimate, scale up

big-\({\cal O}\) estimates (e.g.\({\cal O}(n \log n)\)) are useful but only describe asymptotic scaling

how long will it take? benchmarking

  • test alternative versions of code to compare performance
  • useful for snippets that youre going to put into larger code
  • (thousands of examples on StackOverflow)
  • super-basic: built-in system.time()
  • R packages: rbenchmark, microbenchmark, bench

benchmarking example

(note: dont use textbook formulas like \(\hat \beta = \left(X^\top X\right)^{-1} X^\top y\) in computation!)

set.seed(101)
n <- 100000; p <- 10
X <- matrix(rnorm(n*p), ncol=p); y <- rnorm(n)
naive <- function() c(solve(t(X)%*%X)%*%t(X)%*%y)
smart <- function() unname(coef(lm.fit(X,y)))
all.equal(naive(), smart())  ## check equivalence
## [1] TRUE

benchmarking results

bm(naive(), smart())
## # A tibble: 2  6
##   expression   median `itr/sec` rel_speed mem_alloc rel_mem
##   <bch:expr> <bch:tm>     <dbl>     <dbl> <bch:byt>   <dbl>
## 1 smart()      11.4ms     100.       1       11.5MB    1   
## 2 naive()      18.8ms      58.0      1.73    22.9MB    2.00

profiling

  • Rprof is the basic machine for profiling
    • Rprof() in code outputs profiling information to file
    • R CMD Rprof <filename> analyzes profiling information
  • The Writing R Extensions document has a Tidying and profiling R code section
  • the profvis package provides a prettier wrapper
  • also aprof package

profiling: zero-inflated mixed model example

source("R/zipme.R")  ## get zipme function
load("data/Owls.rda")   ## get Owls data
library(profvis)
library(lme4)
profvis(z1 <- zipme(cformula=SiblingNegotiation~
                (FoodTreatment+ArrivalTime)*SexParent+
                offset(logBroodSize)+(1|Nest),
            zformula=z ~ 1,
            data=Owls,maxitr=20,tol=1e-6,
            verbose=FALSE))

low-hanging fruit

low-hanging fruit

  • Common performance issues
  • Form good R coding habits
  • Many ideas from Burns (2012a) (“If you are using R and you think youre in hell, this is a map for you”)

growing objects (Inferno, circle #2)

  • building up objects bit by bit is super-expensive
  • if i>length(y), setting y[i] will extend the vector
  • growing data frames is even worse
  • use numeric(n) to pre-allocate vectors
  • data.frame(x=numeric(n),...)
  • or: construct a list of data frames and do.call(rbind,dfList) (or dplyr::bind_rows()) to put them together

growing objects: benchmark

n <- 1e4
y <- 1
growing <- function() { for (i in 1:n) y[i] <- i; y }
vec2 <- function() { y <- numeric(n); y <- 1:n; y }
vec <- function() { y <- 1:n; y }
bm(growing(),vec(), vec2())
## # A tibble: 3  6
##   expression   median `itr/sec` rel_speed mem_alloc rel_mem
##   <bch:expr> <bch:tm>     <dbl>     <dbl> <bch:byt>   <dbl>
## 1 vec()      381.03ns  1872760.       1          0B     NaN
## 2 vec2()       6.81s    84966.      22.0   78.17KB     Inf
## 3 growing()    1.81ms      539.    3477.     1.68MB     Inf

vectorization (Inferno, circle #3)

  • Sequential operations expensive; every function call counts
  • Use vectorized operations if possible (e.g.rowMeans(), colMeans())
  • Also: linear algebra (matrix products, Kronecker products, )
y <- numeric(n); x <- 1:n
nonvec <- function() { for (i in 1:n) y[i] <- 2*x[i]; y }
vec <- function() y <- 2*x
bm(nonvec(),vec())
## # A tibble: 2  6
##   expression   median `itr/sec` rel_speed mem_alloc rel_mem
##   <bch:expr> <bch:tm>     <dbl>     <dbl> <bch:byt>   <dbl>
## 1 vec()       10.42s    92682.        1    117.3KB    1.19
## 2 nonvec()     1.17ms      852.      109.    98.4KB    1

vectorization

Suppose we want to compute the means of n1 sets of n2 standard Normal deviates (R/vecrand.R): source("R/vecrand.R")

f1 <-
function (n1 = 1000, n2 = 1000) 
{
    res <- c()
    for (i in 1:n1) {
        x <- c()
        for (j in 1:n2) {
            x <- c(x, rnorm(1))
        }
        res <- c(res, mean(x))
    }
    return(res)
}

double loop, no growing

f2 <-
function (n1 = 1000, n2 = 1000) 
{
    res <- numeric(n1)
    for (i in 1:n1) {
        x <- numeric(n2)
        for (j in 1:n2) {
            x[j] <- rnorm(1)
        }
        res[i] <- mean(x)
    }
    return(res)
}

better versions

f3 <-
function (n1 = 1000, n2 = 1000) 
{
    res <- numeric(n1)
    for (i in 1:n1) {
        res[i] <- mean(rnorm(n2))
    }
    return(res)
}
f4 <-
function (n1 = 1000, n2 = 1000) 
{
    res <- matrix(rnorm(n1 * n2), nrow = n1)
    return(rowMeans(res))
}

benchmark (100x100)

bm(growing=f1(100,100),
   double_loop=f2(100,100),
   single_loop=f3(100,100),
   matrix=f4(100,100),
   iterations=50,
   check = FALSE)
## # A tibble: 4  6
##   expression    median `itr/sec` rel_speed mem_alloc rel_mem
##   <bch:expr>  <bch:tm>     <dbl>     <dbl> <bch:byt>   <dbl>
## 1 matrix       371.8s    2381.       1     157.17KB    1.47
## 2 single_loop    755s    1321.       1.80  106.88KB    1   
## 3 double_loop    8.4ms     119.      20.1   121.55KB    1.14
## 4 growing       11.4ms      87.9     27.1     4.21MB   40.4

over-vectorizing (Inferno, circle #4)

  • sometimes you really cant vectorize
  • e.g.iterative computations
  • difference between for and *apply (and purrr::map) is semantic
  • use what you can understand!

Everyone knows that debugging is twice as hard as writing a program in the first place. So if youre as clever as you can be when you write it, how will you ever debug it? Brian Kernighan

a few more tricks

  • compilation
library(compiler)
cmpfun <- compile(fn)
  • use simpler data structures (matrix faster than data.frame)
  • use the guts of a function to skip data-checking steps: e.g.lm vs lm.fit vs .lm.fit

faster machinery

  • faster linear algebra libraries (Eddelbuettel 2013)
  • Rcpp, Julia,
  • the fastverse

use better packages

  • Task Views (on CRAN)
  • sos::findFn() (full-text search of CRAN)
  • the tidyverse
    • mostly stylistic
    • pipe syntax %>%, |>
    • faster operations on data
  • data.table

asking for help (Inferno #9)

  • include a minimal reproducible example (also see here)
  • include appropriate context (goal, packages, versions, platform)
  • be polite, without groveling
  • be specific: say whats not working
  • say what youve tried/where youve looked
  • dont cross-post

  • d-r-users@mcmaster.ca
  • R mailing lists
  • StackOverflow [r] tag

Getting flamed for asking dumb questions on a public mailing list is all part of growing up and being a man/woman. (Michael Watson, fortunes package)

a final thought on R

The moral of the story is that if you want to create a beautiful language, for gods sake dont make it useful (Burns (2012b), “inferno-ish R”)
